        <paragraphs>
          <p>Function notation is all about describing inputs and outputs. So far we have seen inputs and outputs in these contexts:</p>
            <dl>
              <title></title>
              <li>
                <title>Formulas</title>
                  <p><m>P(t) = 3(1.09)^t</m></p>
                  <p>The value <m>t</m> is the input, and the value <m>P(t)</m> is the result.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <title>Ordered Pairs</title>
                    <p><m>(m, W(m))</m></p>
                    <p>The input <m>m</m> is the horizontal location of a point, and the ouput <m>W(m)</m> is the vertical location of the point.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <title>Tables of Values</title>

                  <table xml:id="function-table">
                  <tabular halign="center" top="medium" left="medium" bottom="medium" right="medium">
                    <row>
                      <cell>x</cell>
                      <cell halign="left">y</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                      <cell>1</cell>
                      <cell halign="left">-3</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                      <cell>2</cell>
                      <cell halign="left">-1</cell>
                    </row>

                    <row>
                      <cell>3</cell>
                      <cell halign="left">7</cell>
                    </row>
                  </tabular>
                </table>
              </li>
            </dl>
            <p>In this section, we explore changes to the input and output of a function.</p>

        </paragraphs>

