    <conclusion>
      <title>Gist of Reflections and Vertical Stretches</title>
      <paragraphs>

        <p>Hopefully you'll agree that saying "the opposite of <m>x</m>" instead of "negative <m>x</m>" makes good sense, especially when we don't know whether <m>x</m> was positive or negative to begin with.</p>
        <p>Now let's put this into practice by writing expressions from a verbal description. For example:</p>
        <blockquote>If <m>f(x)</m> is a function, write an expression which means "five times the output, when the input is the opposite of <m>x</m>".</blockquote>
        <p>The answer would be:</p>
        <blockquote><m>5f(-x)</m></blockquote>
        <p>Now you try it.</p>

      </paragraphs>

    </conclusion>
